TRIP COMMENTS: [I did not record who accompanied me.]  Coverage: we drove around Pond from Southwest corner clockwise. We stopped six or eight times to listen to locate portions of cattails that held each species. We scanned with a scope from the southwest hillside.  Water level full, birds in surrounding vegetation fairly vocal despite rather warm – upper 70s F.  Water level high.  But both Tricolored Blackbirds and Red-winged Blackbirds were singing from various spots in the peninsula and along the southwest corner and north and east of the corner.   No fisherman present. No Least Bittern seen.  Surprisingly absent: other duck species.  Original notes are in file N VAFB Punchbowl 21 September 1996.pdf housed in the Field Note Archive at CCBER.

TRIP COMMENTS: An amazing fall day at SanJoaquin Wildlife Sanctuary (SJWS), before the old duck hunting ponds were completely redone creating very different habitats than what was here during and prior to the mid-1990s. In my field observations notebook for this date I entered that other birders here (not for all of the time noted above, except possibly for Brian and Jeff) on this date included: Brian E. Daniels, Jeff S. Boyd, Mike San Miguel, Loren R. Hays, Curt Johnson, Phil Swan and Laurie Conrad. I didn't record how much area we covered, so guessing on that. Most of the distance was working and re-working the rectangular ponds, where we're at this time mostly dry and supporting just dried out, weedy stubble. I wrote that we covered both the "raised ponds" (the same as Ponds A, B, C, D and E), and the lower, outlying ponds, most of which were dry. ----Weather:  overcast early, becoming partly cloudy, then mostly clear through the remainder of day. 60s to low 70s (deg. F). Breezy at times in afternoon (up to 5-10+ mph, west).
